535/*
536 * There are a few ways to arrive in the initsequencer.
537 * 1. From _PG_init (called exactly once when the library is loaded for ANY
538 * reason).
539 * 1a. Because of the command LOAD 'libraryname';
540 * This case can be distinguished because _PG_init will have found the
541 * LOAD command and saved the 'libraryname' in pljavaLoadPath.
542 * 1b. Because of a CREATE FUNCTION naming this library. pljavaLoadPath will
543 * be NULL.
544 * 1c. By the first actual use of a PL/Java function, causing this library
545 * to be loaded. pljavaLoadPath will be NULL. The called function's Oid
546 * will be available to the call handler once we return from _PG_init,
547 * but it isn't (easily) available here.
548 * 2. From the call handler, if initialization isn't complete yet. That can only
549 * mean something failed in the earlier call to _PG_init, and whatever it was
550 * is highly likely to fail again. That may lead to the untidyness of
551 * duplicated diagnostic messages, but for now I like the belt-and-suspenders
552 * approach of making sure the init sequence gets as many chances as possible
553 * to succeed.
554 * 3. From a GUC assign hook, if the user has updated a setting that might allow
555 * initialization to succeed. It resumes from where it left off.
556 * 4. From the validator handler, if initialization isn't complete yet. That
557 * will definitely happen during pg_upgrade, which is a case where deferInit
558 * will have been set. The validator will then clear deferInit and try to get
559 * further in the init sequence. Importantly, pg_upgrade also sets
560 * check_function_bodies false, which limits the validator's work to a syntax
561 * check of the AS string. The validator therefore will not need to obtain a
562 * schemaLoader or do anything else that requires the sqlj schema to be fully
563 * populated (as, during pg_upgrade, it may not yet be). However, the
564 * validator handler must avoid any action that sets pljavaLoadPath, as a
565 * non-NULL value there would be treated below as case 1a, and trigger an
566 * attempt to set up the sqlj schema.
567 *
568 * In all cases, the sequence must progress as far as starting the VM and
569 * initializing the PL/Java classes. In all cases except 1a, that's enough,
570 * assuming the language handlers and schema have all been set up already (or,
571 * in case 1b, the user is intent on setting them up explicitly).
572 *
573 * In case 1a, we can go ahead and test for, and create, the schema, functions,
574 * and language entries as needed, using pljavaLoadPath as the library path
575 * if creating the language handler functions. One-stop shopping. (The presence
576 * of pljavaLoadPath in any of the other cases, such as resumption by an assign
577 * hook, indicates it is really a continuation of case 1a.)
578 */

743 case IS_JAVAVM_STARTED:

752 case IS_SIGHANDLERS:
753 Invocation_pushBootContext(&ctx);
754 PG_TRY();
755 {
756 initPLJavaClasses();
757 initJavaSession();
758 Invocation_popBootContext();
759 initstage = IS_PLJAVA_FOUND;
760 }
761 PG_CATCH();
762 {
763 MemoryContextSwitchTo(ctx.upperContext); /* leave ErrorContext */
764 Invocation_popBootContext();
765 initstage = IS_MISC_ONCE_DONE;
766 /* We can't stay here...
767 */
768 if ( tolerant )
769 reLogWithChangedLevel(WARNING); /* so xact is not aborted */
770 else
771 {
772 EmitErrorReport(); /* no more unwinding, just log it */
773 /* Seeing an ERROR emitted to the log, without leaving the
774 * transaction aborted, would violate the principle of least
775 * astonishment. But at check_tolerant below, another ERROR will
776 * be thrown immediately, so the transaction effect will be as
777 * expected and this ERROR will contribute information beyond
778 * what is in the generic one thrown down there.
779 */
780 FlushErrorState();
781 }
782 }
783 PG_END_TRY();
784 if ( IS_PLJAVA_FOUND != initstage )
785 {
786 /* JVM initialization failed for some reason. Destroy
787 * the VM if it exists. Perhaps the user will try
788 * fixing the pljava.module_path and make a new attempt.
789 */
790 ereport(WARNING, (
791 errmsg("failed to load initial PL/Java classes"),
792 errhint("The most common reason is that \"pljava.module_path\" "
793 "needs to be set, naming the proper \"pljava.jar\" "
794 "and \"pljava-api.jar\" files, separated by the correct "
795 "path separator for this platform.")
796 ));
797 pljava_DualState_unregister();
798 _destroyJavaVM(0, 0);
799 goto check_tolerant;
800 }
801 /*FALLTHROUGH*/
802
803 case IS_PLJAVA_FOUND:
804 greeting = InstallHelper_hello(); /*adjusts, freezes system properties*/
805 ereport(NULL != pljavaLoadPath ? NOTICE : DEBUG1, (
806 errmsg("PL/Java loaded"),
807 errdetail("versions:\n%s", greeting)));
808 pfree(greeting);
809 initstage = IS_PLJAVA_INSTALLING;
810 /*FALLTHROUGH*/
811
812 case IS_PLJAVA_INSTALLING:
813 if ( NULL != pljavaLoadPath )
814 {
815 warnJEP411 = javaGT11;
816 InstallHelper_groundwork(); /* sqlj schema, language handlers, ...*/
817 }
818 initstage = IS_COMPLETE;
819 /*FALLTHROUGH*/
820
821 case IS_COMPLETE:
822 pljavaLoadingAsExtension = false;
823 if ( alteredSettingsWereNeeded )
824 {
825 /* Use this StringInfoData to conditionally construct part of the
826 * hint string suggesting ALTER DATABASE ... SET ... FROM CURRENT
827 * provided the server is >= 9.2 where that will actually work.
828 * In 9.3, psprintf appeared, which would make this all simpler,
829 * but if 9.3+ were all that had to be supported, this would all
830 * be moot anyway. Doing the initStringInfo inside the ereport
831 * ensures the string is allocated in ErrorContext and won't leak.
832 * Don't remove the extra parens grouping
833 * (initStringInfo, appendStringInfo, errhint) ... with the parens,
834 * that's a comma expression, which is sequenced; without them, they
835 * are just function parameters with evaluation order unknown.
836 */
837 StringInfoData buf;
838
839 ereport(NOTICE, (
840 errmsg("PL/Java successfully started after adjusting settings"),
841 (initStringInfo(&buf),
842 appendStringInfo(&buf, \
843 "using ALTER DATABASE %s SET ... FROM CURRENT or ", \
844 pljavaDbName()),
845 errhint("The settings that worked should be saved (%s"
846 "in the \"%s\" file). For a reminder of what has been set, "
847 "try: SELECT name, setting FROM pg_settings WHERE name LIKE"
848 " 'pljava.%%' AND source = 'session'",
849 buf.data,
850 superuser()
851 ? PG_GETCONFIGOPTION("config_file")
852 : "postgresql.conf"))));
853
854 if ( loadAsExtensionFailed )
855 {
856#if PG_VERSION_NUM < 130000
857#define MOREHINT \
858 "\"CREATE EXTENSION pljava FROM unpackaged\""
859#else
860#define MOREHINT \
861 "\"CREATE EXTENSION pljava VERSION unpackaged\", " \
862 "then (after starting another new session) " \
863 "\"ALTER EXTENSION pljava UPDATE\""
864#endif
865 ereport(NOTICE, (errmsg(
866 "PL/Java load successful after failed CREATE EXTENSION"),
867 errdetail(
868 "PL/Java is now installed, but not as an extension."),
869 errhint(
870 "To correct that, either COMMIT or ROLLBACK, make sure "
871 "the working settings are saved, exit this session, and "
872 "in a new session, either: "
873 "1. if committed, run "
874 MOREHINT
875 ", or 2. "
876 "if rolled back, simply \"CREATE EXTENSION pljava\" again."
877 )));
878#undef MOREHINT
879 }
880 }
881 return;
882
883 default:
884 ereport(ERROR, (
885 errmsg("cannot set up PL/Java"),
886 errdetail(
887 "An unexpected stage was reached in the startup sequence."),
888 errhint(
889 "Please report the circumstances to the PL/Java maintainers.")
890 ));
891 }
892
893check_tolerant:
894 if ( pljavaLoadingAsExtension )
895 {
896 tolerant = false;
897 loadAsExtensionFailed = true;
898 pljavaLoadingAsExtension = false;
899 }
900 if ( !tolerant )
901 {
902 ereport(ERROR, (
903 errcode(ERRCODE_OBJECT_NOT_IN_PREREQUISITE_STATE),
904 errmsg(
905 "cannot use PL/Java before successfully completing its setup"),
906 errhint(
907 "Check the log for messages closely preceding this one, "
908 "detailing what step of setup failed and what will be needed, "
909 "probably setting one of the \"pljava.\" configuration "
910 "variables, to complete the setup. If there is not enough "
911 "help in the log, try again with different settings for "
912 "\"log_min_messages\" or \"log_error_verbosity\".")));
913 }
914}

916/*
917 * A function having everything to do with logging, which ought to be factored
918 * out one day to make a start on the Thoughts-on-logging wiki ideas.
919 */
920static void reLogWithChangedLevel(int level)
921{
922 ErrorData *edata = CopyErrorData();
923 int sqlstate = edata->sqlerrcode;
924 int category = ERRCODE_TO_CATEGORY(sqlstate);
925 FlushErrorState();
926 if ( WARNING > level )
927 {
928 if ( ERRCODE_SUCCESSFUL_COMPLETION != category )
929 sqlstate = ERRCODE_SUCCESSFUL_COMPLETION;
930 }
931 else if ( WARNING == level )
932 {
933 if ( ERRCODE_WARNING != category && ERRCODE_NO_DATA != category )
934 sqlstate = ERRCODE_WARNING;
935 }
936 else if ( ERRCODE_WARNING == category || ERRCODE_NO_DATA == category ||
937 ERRCODE_SUCCESSFUL_COMPLETION == category )
938 sqlstate = ERRCODE_INTERNAL_ERROR;
939
940 edata->elevel = level;
941 edata->sqlerrcode = sqlstate;
942 PG_TRY();
943 {
944 ThrowErrorData(edata);
945 }
946 PG_CATCH();
947 {
948 FreeErrorData(edata); /* otherwise this wouldn't happen in ERROR case */
949 PG_RE_THROW();
950 }
951 PG_END_TRY();
952 FreeErrorData(edata);
953}

955void _PG_init()
956{
957 char *sep;
958
959 if ( IS_PLJAVA_INSTALLING == initstage )
960 return; /* creating handler functions will cause recursive call */
961
962 InstallHelper_earlyHello();
963
964 /*
965 * Find the platform's path separator. Java knows it, but that's no help in
966 * preparing the launch options before it is launched. PostgreSQL knows what
967 * it is, but won't directly say; give it some choices and it'll pick one.
968 * Alternatively, let Maven or Ant determine and add a -D at build time from
969 * the path.separator property. Maybe that's cleaner?
970 */
971 sep = first_path_var_separator(":;");
972 if ( NULL == sep )
973 elog(ERROR,
974 "PL/Java cannot determine the path separator this platform uses");
975 s_path_var_sep = *sep;
976
977 if ( InstallHelper_shouldDeferInit() )
978 deferInit = true;
979 else
980 pljavaCheckExtension( NULL);
981 initsequencer( initstage, true);
982}

1171static jint JNICALL my_vfprintf(FILE* fp, const char* format, va_list args)
1172{
1173 static char const * const cap_format =
1174 "WARNING: JNI local refs: %u, exceeds capacity: %u";
1175 static char const at_prefix[] = "\tat ";
1176 static char const locked_prefix[] = "\t- locked <";
1177 static char const class_prefix[] = "(a ";
1178 static char const culprit[] =
1179 " com.sun.management.internal.DiagnosticCommandImpl.";
1180 static char const nostack[] =
1181 "No stacktrace, probably called from PostgreSQL";
1182 static enum matchstate
1183 {
1184 VFP_INITIAL,
1185 VFP_MAYBE,
1186 VFP_ATE_AT,
1187 VFP_ATE_LOCKED
1188 }
1189 state = VFP_INITIAL;
1190 static unsigned int lastlive, lastcap;
1191
1192 char buf[1024];
1193 char* ep;
1194 char* bp = buf;
1195 unsigned int live, cap;
1196 int got;
1197 char const *detail;
1198
1199 vsnprintf(buf, sizeof(buf), format, args);
1200
1201 /* Try to eliminate annoying -Xcheck:jni messages from deep in JMX that
1202 * nothing can be done about here.
1203 */
1204 for ( ;; state = VFP_INITIAL )
1205 {
1206 switch ( state )
1207 {
1208 case VFP_INITIAL:
1209 got = sscanf(buf, cap_format, &live, &cap);
1210 if ( 2 != got )
1211 break;
1212 lastlive = live;
1213 lastcap = cap;
1214 state = VFP_MAYBE;
1215 return 0;
1216
1217 case VFP_MAYBE:
1218 if ( 0 != strncmp(buf, at_prefix, sizeof at_prefix - 1) )
1219 detail = nostack;
1220 else
1221 {
1222 detail = buf;
1223 state = VFP_ATE_AT;
1224 if ( NULL != strstr(buf, culprit) )
1225 return 0;
1226 }
1227 ereport(INFO, (
1228 errmsg_internal(cap_format, lastlive, lastcap),
1229 errdetail_internal("%s", detail),
1230 errhint(
1231 "To pinpoint location, set a breakpoint on this ereport "
1232 "and follow stacktrace to a functionExit(), its caller "
1233 "(a JNI method), and the immediate caller of that.")));
1234 if ( nostack == detail )
1235 continue;
1236 return 0;
1237
1238 case VFP_ATE_AT:
1239 if ( 0 == strncmp(buf, at_prefix, sizeof at_prefix - 1) )
1240 return 0; /* remain in ATE_AT state */
1241 if ( 0 != strncmp(buf, locked_prefix, sizeof locked_prefix - 1) )
1242 continue;
1243 state = VFP_ATE_LOCKED;
1244 return 0;
1245
1246 case VFP_ATE_LOCKED:
1247 if ( 0 != strncmp(buf, class_prefix, sizeof class_prefix - 1) )
1248 continue;
1249 state = VFP_ATE_AT;
1250 return 0;
1251 }
1252 break;
1253 }
1254
1255 /* Trim off trailing newline and other whitespace.
1256 */
1257 ep = bp + strlen(bp) - 1;
1258 while(ep >= bp && isspace(*ep))
1259 --ep;
1260 ++ep;
1261 *ep = 0;
1262
1263 elog(s_javaLogLevel, "%s", buf);
1264 return 0;
1265}

1267/*
1268 * Append those parts of path that has not yet been appended. The HashMap unique is
1269 * keeping track of what has been appended already. First appended part will be
1270 * prefixed with prefix.
1271 */
1272static void appendPathParts(const char* path, StringInfoData* bld, HashMap unique, const char* prefix)
1273{
1274 StringInfoData buf;
1275 if(path == 0 || strlen(path) == 0)
1276 return;
1277
1278 for (;;)
1279 {
1280 char* pathPart;
1281 char* sep;
1282 size_t len;
1283
1284 if(*path == 0)
1285 break;
1286
1287 sep = first_path_var_separator(path);
1288
1289 if(sep == path)
1290 {
1291 /* Ignore zero length components.
1292 */
1293 ++path;
1294 continue;
1295 }
1296
1297 if ( NULL == sep )
1298 len = strlen(path);
1299 else
1300 len = sep - path;
1301
1302 initStringInfo(&buf);
1303 if(*path == '$')
1304 {
1305 if( (len == 7 || first_dir_separator(path) == path + 7)
1306 && strncmp(path, "$libdir", 7) == 0)
1307 {
1308 char pathbuf[MAXPGPATH];
1309 get_pkglib_path(my_exec_path, pathbuf);
1310 len -= 7;
1311 path += 7;
1312 appendStringInfoString(&buf, pathbuf);
1313 }
1314 else
1315 ereport(ERROR, (
1316 errcode(ERRCODE_INVALID_NAME),
1317 errmsg("invalid macro name '%*s' in PL/Java module path",
1318 (int)len, path)));
1319 }
1320
1321 if(len > 0)
1322 {
1323 appendBinaryStringInfo(&buf, path, (int)len);
1324 path += len;
1325 }
1326
1327 pathPart = buf.data;
1328 if(HashMap_getByString(unique, pathPart) == 0)
1329 {
1330 if(HashMap_size(unique) == 0)
1331 appendStringInfo(bld, "%s", prefix);
1332 else
1333 appendStringInfoChar(bld, s_path_var_sep);
1334 appendStringInfo(bld, "%s", pathPart);
1335 HashMap_putByString(unique, pathPart, (void*)1);
1336 }
1337 pfree(pathPart);
1338 if(*path == 0)
1339 break;
1340 ++path; /* Skip path var separator */
1341 }
1342}
1343
1344/*
1345 * Get the module path. Result is always freshly palloc'd.
1346 * No longer relies on an environment variable. What CLASSPATH variable might
1347 * happen to be randomly set in the environment of a PostgreSQL backend?
1348 */
1349static char* getModulePath(const char* prefix)
1350{
1351 char* path;
1352 HashMap unique = HashMap_create(13, CurrentMemoryContext);
1353 StringInfoData buf;
1354 initStringInfo(&buf);
1355 appendPathParts(modulepath, &buf, unique, prefix);
1356 PgObject_free((PgObject)unique);
1357 path = buf.data;
1358 if(strlen(path) == 0)
1359 {
1360 pfree(path);
1361 path = 0;
1362 }
1363 return path;
1364}

1401static sigjmp_buf recoverBuf;
1402static void terminationTimeoutHandler()
1403{
1404 kill(MyProcPid, SIGQUIT);
1405
1406 /* Some sleep to get the SIGQUIT a chance to generate
1407 * the needed output.
1408 */
1409 pg_usleep(1);
1410
1411 /* JavaVM did not die within the alloted time
1412 */
1413 siglongjmp(recoverBuf, 1);
1414}

1417/*
1418 * proc_exit callback to tear down the JVM
1419 */
1420static void _destroyJavaVM(int status, Datum dummy)
1421{
1422 if(s_javaVM != 0)
1423 {
1424 Invocation ctx;
1425#ifdef USE_PLJAVA_SIGHANDLERS
1426 TimeoutId tid;
1427
1428 Invocation_pushBootContext(&ctx);
1429 if(sigsetjmp(recoverBuf, 1) != 0)
1430 {
1431 elog(DEBUG2,
1432 "needed to forcibly shut down the Java virtual machine");
1433 s_javaVM = 0;
1434 currentInvocation = 0;
1435 return;
1436 }
1437
1438 tid = RegisterTimeout(USER_TIMEOUT, terminationTimeoutHandler);
1439 enable_timeout_after(tid, 5000);
1440
1441 elog(DEBUG2, "shutting down the Java virtual machine");
1442 JNI_destroyVM(s_javaVM);
1443
1444 disable_timeout(tid, false);
1445#else
1446 Invocation_pushBootContext(&ctx);
1447 elog(DEBUG2, "shutting down the Java virtual machine");
1448 JNI_destroyVM(s_javaVM);
1449#endif
1450 elog(DEBUG2, "done shutting down the Java virtual machine");
1451 s_javaVM = 0;
1452 currentInvocation = 0;
1453 }
1454}

1463static void JVMOptList_delete(JVMOptList* jol)
1464{
1465 JavaVMOption* opt = jol->options;
1466 JavaVMOption* top = opt + jol->size;
1467 while(opt < top)
1468 {
1469 pfree(opt->optionString);
1470 opt++;
1471 }
1472 pfree(jol->options);

1475static void JVMOptList_add(JVMOptList* jol, const char* optString, void* extraInfo, bool mustCopy)
1476{
1477 JavaVMOption* added;
1478
1479 int newPos = jol->size;
1480 if(newPos >= jol->capacity)
1481 {
1482 int newCap = jol->capacity * 2;
1483 JavaVMOption* newOpts = (JavaVMOption*)palloc(newCap * sizeof(JavaVMOption));
1484 memcpy(newOpts, jol->options, newPos * sizeof(JavaVMOption));
1485 pfree(jol->options);
1486 jol->options = newOpts;
1487 jol->capacity = newCap;
1488 }
1489 added = jol->options + newPos;
1490 if(mustCopy)
1491 optString = pstrdup(optString);
1492
1493 added->optionString = (char*)optString;
1494 added->extraInfo = extraInfo;
1495 jol->size++;
1496
1497 if ( 0 == strncmp(optString, visualVMprefix, sizeof visualVMprefix - 1) )
1498 seenVisualVMName = true;
1499
1500 if ( 0 == strncmp(optString, moduleMainPrefix, sizeof moduleMainPrefix-1) )
1501 seenModuleMain = true;
1502
1503 elog(DEBUG2, "Added JVM option string \"%s\"", optString);
1504}

1523 initStringInfo(&buf);
1524 appendStringInfo(&buf, "%s%s",
1525 moduleMainPrefix, "org.postgresql.pljava");
1526 JVMOptList_add(jol, buf.data, 0, false);
1527}
1528
1529/* Split JVM options. The string is split on whitespace unless the
1530 * whitespace is found within a string or is escaped by backslash. A
1531 * backslash escaped quote is not considered a string delimiter.
1532 */
1533static void addUserJVMOptions(JVMOptList* optList)
1534{
1535 const char* cp = vmoptions;
1536
1537 if(cp != NULL)
1538 {
1539 StringInfoData buf;
1540 char quote = 0;
1541 char c;
1542
1543 initStringInfo(&buf);
1544 for(;;)
1545 {
1546 c = *cp++;
1547 switch(c)
1548 {
1549 case 0:
1550 break;
1551
1552 case '"':
1553 case '\'':
1554 if(quote == c)
1555 quote = 0;
1556 else
1557 quote = c;
1558 appendStringInfoChar(&buf, c);
1559 continue;
1560
1561 case '\\':
1562 appendStringInfoChar(&buf, '\\');
1563 c = *cp++; /* Interpret next character verbatim */
1564 if(c == 0)
1565 break;
1566 appendStringInfoChar(&buf, c);
1567 continue;
1568
1569 default:
1570 if(quote == 0 && isspace((int)c))
1571 {
1572 while((c = *cp++) != 0)
1573 {
1574 if(!isspace((int)c))
1575 break;
1576 }
1577
1578 if(c == 0)
1579 break;
1580
1581 if(c != '-')
1582 appendStringInfoChar(&buf, ' ');
1583 else if(buf.len > 0)
1584 {
1585 /* Whitespace followed by '-' triggers new
1586 * option declaration.
1587 */
1588 JVMOptList_add(optList, buf.data, 0, true);
1589 buf.len = 0;
1590 buf.data[0] = 0;
1591 }
1592 }
1593 appendStringInfoChar(&buf, c);
1594 continue;
1595 }
1596 break;
1597 }
1598 if(buf.len > 0)
1599 JVMOptList_add(optList, buf.data, 0, true);
1600 pfree(buf.data);
1601 }
1602}

1634static jint initializeJavaVM(JVMOptList *optList)
1635{
1636 jint jstat;
1637 JavaVMInitArgs vm_args;
1638
1639 if(pljavaDebug)
1640 {
1641 elog(INFO, "Backend pid = %d. Attach the debugger and set pljavaDebug to false to continue", getpid());
1642 while(pljavaDebug)
1643 pg_usleep(1000000L);
1644 }
1645
1646 vm_args.nOptions = optList->size;
1647 vm_args.options = optList->options;
1648 vm_args.version = JNI_VERSION_9;
1649 vm_args.ignoreUnrecognized = JNI_FALSE;
1650
1651 elog(DEBUG2, "creating Java virtual machine");
1652
1653 jstat = JNI_createVM(&s_javaVM, &vm_args);
1654
1655 if(jstat == JNI_OK && JNI_exceptionCheck())
1656 {
1657 JNI_exceptionDescribe();
1658 JNI_exceptionClear();
1659 jstat = JNI_ERR;
1660 }
1661 JVMOptList_delete(optList);
1662
1663 return jstat;
1664}

1913static inline Datum
1914internalCallHandler(bool trusted, PG_FUNCTION_ARGS)
1915{
1916 Invocation ctx;
1917 Datum retval = 0;
1918 Oid funcoid = fcinfo->flinfo->fn_oid;
1919 bool forTrigger = CALLED_AS_TRIGGER(fcinfo);
1920
1921 /*
1922 * Just in case it could be helpful in offering diagnostics later, hang
1923 * on to an Oid that is known to refer to PL/Java (because it got here).
1924 * It's cheap, and can be followed back to the right language and
1925 * handler function entries later if needed.
1926 */
1927 *(trusted ? &pljavaTrustedOid : &pljavaUntrustedOid) = funcoid;
1928 if ( IS_COMPLETE != initstage )
1929 {
1930 deferInit = false;
1931 initsequencer( initstage, false);
1932 }
1933
1934 Invocation_pushInvocation(&ctx);
1935 PG_TRY();
1936 {
1937 retval = Function_invoke(
1938 funcoid, trusted, forTrigger, false, true, fcinfo);
1939 Invocation_popInvocation(false);
1940 }
1941 PG_CATCH();
1942 {
1943 Invocation_popInvocation(true);
1944 PG_RE_THROW();
1945 }
1946 PG_END_TRY();
1947 return retval;
1948}

1967
1968static Datum internalValidator(bool trusted, PG_FUNCTION_ARGS)
1969{
1970 Oid funcoid = PG_GETARG_OID(0);
1971 Invocation ctx;
1972 Oid *oidSaveLocation = NULL;
1973
1974 bool ok = CheckFunctionValidatorAccess(fcinfo->flinfo->fn_oid, funcoid);
1975 /*
1976 * CheckFunctionValidatorAccess reserves a possible future behavior where
1977 * it returns false and this validator should immediately return. Here we
1978 * abuse that convention slightly by first checking an additional constraint
1979 * on function creation in withoutEnforcing mode. That, arguably, is a check
1980 * that should never be skipped, just like the permission checks made in
1981 * CheckFunctionValidatorAccess itself.
1982 */
1983 if ( withoutEnforcement && trusted && ! superuser() )
1984 ereport(ERROR, (
1985 errmsg(
1986 "trusted PL/Java language restricted to superuser when "
1987 "\"java.security.manager\"=\"disallow\""),
1988 errdetail(
1989 "This PL/Java version enforces security policy using important "
1990 "Java features that upstream Java has disabled as of Java 24, "
1991 "as described in JEP 486. In Java 18 through 23, enforcement is "
1992 "still available, but requires "
1993 "\"-Djava.security.manager=allow\" in \"pljava.vmoptions\". "
1994 "The alternative \"-Djava.security.manager=disallow\" permits "
1995 "use on Java 24 and later, but with no enforcement and no "
1996 "distinction between trusted and untrusted. In this mode, only "
1997 "a superuser may use even a 'trusted' PL/Java language")
1998 ));
1999 if ( ! ok )
2000 PG_RETURN_VOID();
2001
2002 /*
2003 * In the call handler, which could be called heavily, funcoid gets
2004 * unconditionally stored to one of these two locations, rather than
2005 * spending extra cycles deciding whether to store it or not. A validator
2006 * will not be called as heavily, and can afford to check here whether
2007 * an Oid needs to be stored or not. The situation to avoid is where
2008 * funcoid gets stored here, as an Oid from which PL/Java's library path can
2009 * be found, but the function then gets rejected by the validator, leaving
2010 * the stored Oid invalid and useless for that purpose. Therefore, choose
2011 * here whether and where to store it, but store it only within the PG_TRY
2012 * block, and replace with InvalidOid again in the PG_CATCH.
2013 */
2014 if ( trusted )
2015 {
2016 if ( InvalidOid == pljavaTrustedOid )
2017 oidSaveLocation = &pljavaTrustedOid;
2018 }
2019 else
2020 {
2021 if ( InvalidOid == pljavaUntrustedOid )
2022 oidSaveLocation = &pljavaUntrustedOid;
2023 }
2024
2025 if ( IS_PLJAVA_INSTALLING > initstage )
2026 {
2027 if ( check_function_bodies ) /* We're gonna need a JVM */
2028 {
2029 deferInit = false;
2030 initsequencer( initstage, false);
2031 }
2032 else /* Can try to start one, but if no go, just assume function's ok */
2033 {
2034 initsequencer( initstage, true);
2035 if ( IS_PLJAVA_INSTALLING > initstage )
2036 {
2037 if ( javaGT11 )
2038 warnJEP411 = true;
2039 PG_RETURN_VOID();
2040 }
2041 }
2042 }
2043
2044 Invocation_pushInvocation(&ctx);
2045 PG_TRY();
2046 {
2047 if ( NULL != oidSaveLocation )
2048 *oidSaveLocation = funcoid;
2049
2050 Function_invoke(
2051 funcoid, trusted, false, true, check_function_bodies, NULL);
2052 Invocation_popInvocation(false);
2053 }
2054 PG_CATCH();
2055 {
2056 if ( NULL != oidSaveLocation )
2057 *oidSaveLocation = InvalidOid;
2058
2059 Invocation_popInvocation(true);
2060 PG_RE_THROW();
2061 }
2062 PG_END_TRY();
2063
2064 if ( javaGT11 )
2065 warnJEP411 = true;
2066 PG_RETURN_VOID();
2067}
2068
2069/*
2070 * Called at the ends of committing transactions to emit a warning about future
2071 * JEP 411 impacts, at most once per session, if any PL/Java functions were
2072 * declared or redeclared in the transaction, or if PL/Java was installed or
2073 * upgraded. Also called from InstallHelper, if pg_upgrade is happening.
2074 * Yes, this is a bit tangled. The tracking of function declaration happens
2075 * above in the validator handler, and PL/Java installation/upgrade is detected
2076 * in the initsequencer.
2077 */
2078void Backend_warnJEP411(bool isCommit)
2079{
2080 static bool warningEmitted = false; /* once only per session */
2081
2082 if ( ! warnJEP411 || withoutEnforcement || warningEmitted )
2083 return;
2084
2085 if ( ! isCommit )
2086 {
2087 warnJEP411 = false;
2088 return;
2089 }
2090
2091 warningEmitted = true;
2092
2093 ereport(javaGE17 ? WARNING : NOTICE, (
2094 errmsg(
2095 "[JEP 411] migration advisory: Java version 24 and later "
2096 "cannot run PL/Java %s with policy enforcement", SO_VERSION_STRING),
2097 errdetail(
2098 "This PL/Java version enforces security policy using important "
2099 "Java features that upstream Java has disabled as of Java 24, "
2100 "as described in JEP 486. In Java 18 through 23, enforcement is "
2101 "still available, but requires "
2102 "\"-Djava.security.manager=allow\" in \"pljava.vmoptions\". "),
2103 errhint(
2104 "For migration planning, this version of PL/Java can still "
2105 "enforce policy in Java versions up to and including 23, "
2106 "and Java 17 and 21 are positioned as long-term support releases. "
2107 "Java 24 and later can be used, if wanted, WITH ABSOLUTELY NO "
2108 "EXPECTATIONS OF SECURITY POLICY ENFORCEMENT, by adding "
2109 "\"-Djava.security.manager=disallow\" in \"pljava.vmoptions\". "
2110 "This mode should be considered only if all Java code to be used "
2111 "is considered well vetted and trusted. "
2112 "For details on how PL/Java will adapt, please bookmark "
2113 "https://github.com/tada/pljava/wiki/JEP-411")
2114 ));
2115}

2303/*
2304 * Class: org_postgresql_pljava_internal_Backend
2305 * Method: _pokeJEP411
2306 * Signature: (Ljava/lang/Class;Ljava/lang/Object;)V
2307 *
2308 * This method is hideously dependent on unexposed JDK internals. But then,
2309 * the fact that it's needed at all is hideous already. Java, any language,
2310 * is classic infrastructure. Other layers, like this, are built atop it, and
2311 * others in turn use those layers. The idea that the language developers would
2312 * arrogate to themselves the act of sending an inappropriately low-level
2313 * message directly to ultimate users, insisting that the stack layers above
2314 * cannot intercept it and notify the higher-level users in terms that fit
2315 * the abstractions meaningful there, leaves an uneasy picture of how
2316 * a development team can begin to lose sight of who is providing what to whom
2317 * and why.
2318 *
2319 * At least as of the time of this writing, System has a CallersHolder class
2320 * holding a map recording classes for which the warning has already been sent.
2321 * Poking the 'caller' class into that map works to suppress the warning.
2322 */
2323JNIEXPORT void JNICALL
2324Java_org_postgresql_pljava_internal_Backend__1pokeJEP411(JNIEnv *env, jclass cls, jclass caller, jobject token)
2325{
2326 jclass callersHolder;
2327 jfieldID callers;
2328 jobject map;
2329 jclass mapClass;
2330 jmethodID put;
2331
2332 BEGIN_NATIVE
2333
2334 callersHolder = JNI_findClass("java/lang/System$CallersHolder");
2335 if ( NULL == callersHolder )
2336 goto failed;
2337
2338 callers = JNI_getStaticFieldID(callersHolder, "callers", "Ljava/util/Map;");
2339 if ( NULL == callers )
2340 goto failed;
2341
2342 map = JNI_getStaticObjectField(callersHolder, callers);
2343 if ( NULL == map )
2344 goto failed;
2345
2346 mapClass = JNI_getObjectClass(map);
2347 put = JNI_getMethodID(mapClass,
2348 "put", "(Ljava/lang/Object;Ljava/lang/Object;)Ljava/lang/Object;");
2349
2350 JNI_callObjectMethodLocked(map, put, caller, token);
2351 goto done;
2352
2353failed:
2354 JNI_exceptionClear();
2355
2356done:
2357 END_NATIVE
